11_9	0.07824721	But these GPS readings have only been taken once a year; a new system, using GPS receivers that continuously send position information, is being installed to replace the decade-old stations.
11_10	0.084379207	But only one station is operational.
11_11	0.093470695	If a network of the new monitors had been in place, Toksoz said, ``we might have been able to predict the quake and provide some warning''.
11_12	0.0768592	That warning might have been anywhere from a few minutes to a few hours before the shaking began, he said, providing enough time for people to leave vulnerable buildings, and perhaps even to store water and supplies.
11_13	0.084577995	A real-time warning based on GPS data has never been issued, Toksoz said.
11_14	0.082268692	But the only similar networks of monitoring stations in the world, one in Japan and one in southern California, have shown distinct signs of some impending earthquakes when scientists have looked back at the records after a quake occurred.
11_15	0.084846567	``People have detected precursor motions,'' Toksoz said, ``but not in real time''.
11_16	0.093011163	With the added impetus of this quake, he said, ``we'll push on with it''.
11_17	0.090836155	He said earthquakes have been gradually migrating westward along the North Anatolian fault, as stress builds up in the rock and is then released.
11_18	0.098805936	The largest earthquake ever recorded on the fault was a magnitude 8.2 quake in 1939, which killed 20,000 people, and there have been six other quakes greater than magnitude 7 since then, each spanning a 60- to 100-mile segment of the fault.
11_19	0.095667836	Istanbul, Turkey's largest city, with a population of 12 million, lies just 65 miles west of Izmit, and may be the next place to feel the fault's wrath.
11_20	0.0866108	The fault line, which closely resembles California's San Andreas fault, passes just a few miles from the city.
11_21	0.095627788	Geologists call both faults right-handed strike-slip faults.
11_22	0.10991059	The Izmit earthquake may actually have increased the stresses on the Istanbul segment of the fault, increasing the odds of a major quake there in coming years.
11_23	0.097953632	``We're very much concerned about what might happen in that area,'' Toksoz said.
11_24	0.07912947	``There is the potential for a major earthquake''.
11_25	0.10439447	There is an earthquake building code in place in the city, he said, ``but unfortunately, implementation is lax''.
11_26	0.094717086	As a result, he said, a major quake striking the city ``could be an economic disaster as well as a human disaster''.
